<h2>What Is A Crypto Exchange?</h2>
<p><span data-color="var(--green-10)">A crypto exchange is a digital marketplace where you can buy and sell cryptocurrencies. Think of it as a stock broker, but for digital assets like Bitcoin, Ethereum, and thousands of other cryptocurrencies.</span></p>
<h3><span data-color="var(--green-10)">What Are The Types of Exchanges and Geographic Restrictions?</span></h3>
<p><span data-color="var(--green-10)">There are two main types of crypto platforms, and understanding the difference is key to finding the one for you.</span></p>
<ul>
<li><span data-color="var(--green-10)">Centralized Exchanges (CEX): This is what most people think of. Platforms like Binance, Bitget, and Crypto.com are centralized exchanges. They are private companies that act as a trusted middleman or brokers to store altcoins, manage trades, secure funds, and provide customer support services.</span></li>
<li><span data-color="var(--green-10)">Decentralized Exchanges (DEX): Platforms like Uniswap or SushiSwap are DEXs. They are great to swap crypto not for storing. They run on blockchain technology (smart contracts) and operate without a central authority. While they offer more control for investment than centralized exchanges, they are more difficult to use.</span></li>
</ul>
<p><span data-color="var(--green-10)">Many global exchanges do not serve residents in some countries and regions (includin the U.S., the U.K., China, Japan, and some EU countries) due to their regulations. Geographic restrictions apply through IP blocking, KYC requirements, and bank account transfer limitations. Because geographic restrictions apply, ensure to research before signing up.</span></p>
<h3>Are Crypto Exchanges Safe?</h3>
<p><span data-color="var(--green-10)">The top platforms are generally considered safe, but the risk is never zero. Since they hold and control their users&#8217; funds, they are major targets for hackers, and the industry has a history of high-profile failures.</span></p>
<p>However, the best platforms in 2026 invest millions in security. They use:</p>
<ul>
<li><span data-color="var(--green-10)">Cold Storage: Keeping the vast majority of their users offline, safe from hackers.</span></li>
<li>Two-Factor Authentication (2FA): Protecting your account from unauthorized logins.</li>
<li>Proof of Reserves (PoR): Public audits showing they hold user assets 1:1.</li>
<li><span data-color="var(--green-10)">Insurance Funds: Many exchanges(like Binance&#8217;s “SAFU”) have funds to reimburse customers in case of a hack.</span></li>
</ul>
